578 /**
579  * @brief Constructs a new Ec2Client object.
580  *
581  * @param region AWS region for this client to service requests for.
582  * @param credentials AWS credentials to use for signing requests.
583  * @param manager Network access manager for sending requests.
584  * @param parent This object's parent.
585  */
586 Ec2Client::Ec2Client(
587  const QtAws::Core::AwsRegion::Region region,
588  QtAws::Core::AwsAbstractCredentials * credentials,
589  QNetworkAccessManager * const manager,
590  QObject * const parent)
591 : QtAws::Core::AwsAbstractClient(new Ec2ClientPrivate(this), parent)
592 {
593  Q_D(Ec2Client);
594  d->apiVersion = QStringLiteral("2016-11-15");
595  d->credentials = credentials;
596  d->endpointPrefix = QStringLiteral("ec2");
597  d->networkAccessManager = manager;
598  d->region = region;
599  d->serviceFullName = QStringLiteral("Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud");
600  d->serviceName = QStringLiteral("ec2");
601 }

610  * automatically (via AwsEndpoint::getEndpoint).

1062  * ICMP type and code. You can use -1 for the type or code to mean all types or all codes. You can optionally specify a
1063  * description for the
1064  *
1065  * rule>

1068  *

1897  * traffic>

3786 /**
3787  * Describes your account's Reserved Instance listings in the Reserved Instance
3788  *
3789  * Marketplace>
3790  *
3791  * The Reserved Instance Marketplace matches sellers who want to resell Reserved Instance capacity that they no longer need
3792  * with buyers who want to purchase additional capacity. Reserved Instances bought and sold through the Reserved Instance
3793  * Marketplace work like any other Reserved
3794  *
3795  * Instances>
3796  *
3797  * As a seller, you choose to list some or all of your Reserved Instances, and you specify the upfront price to receive for
3798  * them. Your Reserved Instances are then listed in the Reserved Instance Marketplace and are available for
3799  *
3800  * purchase>
3801  *
3802  * As a buyer, you specify the configuration of the Reserved Instance to purchase, and the Marketplace matches what you're
3803  * searching for with what's available. The Marketplace first sells the lowest priced Reserved Instances to you, and
3804  * continues to sell available Reserved Instance listings to you until your demand is met. You are charged based on the
3805  * total price of all of the listings that you
3806  *

4253 /**
4254  * Describes the status of the specified volumes. Volume status provides the result of the checks performed on your volumes
4255  * to determine events that can impair the performance of your volumes. The performance of a volume can be affected if an
4256  * issue occurs on the volume's underlying host. If the volume's underlying host experiences a power outage or system
4257  * issue, after the system is restored, there could be data inconsistencies on the volume. Volume events notify you if this
4258  * occurs. Volume actions notify you if any action needs to be taken in response to the
4259  *
4260  * event>
4261  *
4262  * The <code>DescribeVolumeStatus</code> operation provides the following information about the specified
4263  *
4264  * volumes>
4265  *
4266  * <i>Status</i>: Reflects the current status of the volume. The possible values are <code>ok</code>, <code>impaired</code>
4267  * , <code>warning</code>, or <code>insufficient-data</code>. If all checks pass, the overall status of the volume is
4268  * <code>ok</code>. If the check fails, the overall status is <code>impaired</code>. If the status is
4269  * <code>insufficient-data</code>, then the checks may still be taking place on your volume at the time. We recommend that
4270  * you retry the request. For more information on volume status, see <a
4271  * href="http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/monitoring-volume-status.html">Monitoring the Status of Your
4272  *
4273  * Volumes</a>>
4274  *
4275  * <i>Events</i>: Reflect the cause of a volume status and may require you to take action. For example, if your volume
4276  * returns an <code>impaired</code> status, then the volume event might be <code>potential-data-inconsistency</code>. This
4277  * means that your volume has been affected by an issue with the underlying host, has all I/O operations disabled, and may
4278  * have inconsistent
4279  *
4280  * data>
4281  *
4282  * <i>Actions</i>: Reflect the actions you may have to take in response to an event. For example, if the status of the
4283  * volume is <code>impaired</code> and the volume event shows <code>potential-data-inconsistency</code>, then the action
4284  * shows <code>enable-volume-io</code>. This means that you may want to enable the I/O operations for the volume by calling
4285  * the <a>EnableVolumeIO</a> action and then check the volume for data
4286  *
4287  * consistency> <note>
4288  *
4289  * Volume status is based on the volume status checks, and does not reflect the volume state. Therefore, volume status does
4290  * not indicate volumes in the <code>error</code> state (for example, when a volume is incapable of accepting
4291  *
4292  * @param request Request to send to Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud.
4293  *
4294  * @return A pointer to a related response object.
4295  *
4296  * @note The caller is to take responsbility for the resulting pointer.
4297  */

4330 /**
4331  * Reports the current modification status of EBS
4332  *
4333  * volumes>
4334  *
4335  * Current-generation EBS volumes support modification of attributes including type, size, and (for <code>io1</code>
4336  * volumes) IOPS provisioning while either attached to or detached from an instance. Following an action from the API or
4337  * the console to modify a volume, the status of the modification may be <code>modifying</code>, <code>optimizing</code>,
4338  * <code>completed</code>, or <code>failed</code>. If a volume has never been modified, then certain elements of the
4339  * returned <code>VolumeModification</code> objects are null.
4340  *
4341  * </p
4342  *

4344  * CloudWatch Events, see the <a href="http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/events/">Amazon CloudWatch Events
4345  * User Guide</a>. For more information, see <a
4346  * href="http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/ebs-expand-volume.html#monitoring_mods">Monitoring Volume
4347  * Modifications"</a>.

5407  * While the Spot Fleet request is being modified, it is in the <code>modifying</code>
5408  *
5409  * state>
5410  *
5411  * To scale up your Spot Fleet, increase its target capacity. The Spot Fleet launches the additional Spot Instances
5412  * according to the allocation strategy for the Spot Fleet request. If the allocation strategy is <code>lowestPrice</code>,
5413  * the Spot Fleet launches instances using the Spot pool with the lowest price. If the allocation strategy is
5414  * <code>diversified</code>, the Spot Fleet distributes the instances across the Spot
5415  *
5416  * pools>
5417  *
5418  * To scale down your Spot Fleet, decrease its target capacity. First, the Spot Fleet cancels any open requests that exceed
5419  * the new target capacity. You can request that the Spot Fleet terminate Spot Instances until the size of the fleet no
5420  * longer exceeds the new target capacity. If the allocation strategy is <code>lowestPrice</code>, the Spot Fleet
5421  * terminates the instances with the highest price per unit. If the allocation strategy is <code>diversified</code>, the
5422  * Spot Fleet terminates instances across the Spot pools. Alternatively, you can request that the Spot Fleet keep the fleet
5423  * at its current size, but not replace any Spot Instances that are interrupted or that you terminate
5424  *
5425  * manually>
5426  *
5427  * If you are finished with your Spot Fleet for now, but will use it again later, you can set the target capacity to
5428  *
5429  * @param request Request to send to Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud.
